<HEAD>Government Begins Emergency Plan to Control Fires in Amazon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By Jorge Mederos</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government official said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> police
are fighting indiscriminate burning and tree-cutting in parts of the
<LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> rain forest under emergency measures that already have
brought <MONEY>$9 million</MONEY> in fines.
   <PERSON>Jose Roberto Lima</PERSON>, a spokesman for the state's <ORGANIZATION>Brazilian
Environmental Institute</ORGANIZATION>, said institute agents and federal police
began patrolling part of the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> jungle in five helicopters in
early <DATE>August</DATE>.
   In that month, ranchers and farmers traditionally begin to burn
off forest growth for pasture and planting.
   ``The area is wild and the settlers extremely dangerous. If you
don't police the jungle with a machine gun on your side, you're as
good as dead,'' <LOCATION>Lima</LOCATION> said in an interview.
   He said agents had handed out fines of about <MONEY>$9 million</MONEY> in the
<DATE>first 15 days</DATE> of the exercise.
   Among those fined were farmers, ranchers, steel mills that use
wood to fuel blast furnaces and 15 sawmills.
   <LOCATION>Lima</LOCATION> said fines will be used to support an emergency
environmental package called ``Our Nature'' announced earlier this
year.
   Amid mounting world concern that the destruction of the forest
could disastrously change global weather, the Brazilian government
also this year suspended incentives for large-scale agricultural and
cattle ranching projects and created a special police force to
control fires.
   Satellite photographs show that in the past 10 years the 2
million-square-mile rain forest, the world's largest, has lost an
area half the size of <LOCATION>West Virginia</LOCATION> to slashing, burning and mining.
   Ecologists charge the government has done little to discourage
the uncontrolled destruction.
   <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> initially refused offers of help from international
organizations and foreign governments, saying that would amount to
meddling in its internal affairs but has softened that position in
recent months.
   The government earlier this year turned down offers from the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Netherlands</LOCATION> to discuss swapping part
of <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s <MONEY>$115 million</MONEY> debt for preserving <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> land, which
covers two-thirds of <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> and is home to 15 million people.
   But <LOCATION>Lima</LOCATION> said the institute hopes to receive help from foreign
governments to strengthen its efforts.
   <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> already have promised five tanker planes to help
put out forest fires, he said.
   In just 25 hours of flights over the so-called <ORGANIZATION>Parrot</ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION>Beak</LOCATION>
region in southern Para _ the site of bloody clashes between peasant
farmers and large landowners _ agents found 150 areas where the
forest was being illegally destroyed, <LOCATION>Lima</LOCATION> said.
   He said the patrols have rescued 150 animals and 120 birds, some
threatened with extinction.
   The patrols will continue for three months over the jungle states
of <LOCATION>Para</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Mato Grosso</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Rondonia</LOCATION> and Acre, <LOCATION>Lima</LOCATION> said. The so-called
Legal <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> also includes the states of <LOCATION>Amapa</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Roraima</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Maranhao</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Tocantins</LOCATION> and Amazonas.
   Uncontrolled colonization has destroyed more than <PERCENT>5 percent</PERCENT> of
the rain forest, satellite photos show. Some researchers put the
figure at nearer <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT>.
</TEXT>
