<HEAD>Timber Industry Approves Environment Plan for Amazon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MUELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservation groups applauded a
decision <DATE>Friday</DATE> by the international timber industry to promote
environment-conscious logging in the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> jungle, the world's
largest tropical rainforest.
   The U.S.-based World Wildlife Fund said the decision _ the first
of its kind by the timber industry _ could slow destruction of the
<LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> rainforest, a key regulator of the world's weather.
   The <ORGANIZATION>International Tropical Timber Organization</ORGANIZATION>, an association
of 42 producing and consuming countries, approved a <MONEY>$4 million</MONEY>
logging and conservation project in the remote jungle state of
Acre, on <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s border with <LOCATION>Bolivia</LOCATION>, 2,800 miles northwest of <ORGANIZATION>Rio
de Janeiro</ORGANIZATION>.
   The project calls for ``integrated'' development of jungle
products, such as <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> nuts and rubber, as well as timber. It
also calls for loggers to consult with environmental groups,
government agencies, native Indians and local workers to plan
long-term development to preserve the rainforest.
   ``This was the big one. We hope the Acre project can serve as a
model not just for the rest of the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> but for all tropical
forests,'' <PERSON>Adam Markham</PERSON>, press spokesman for the World Wildlife
Fund, told the AP at the end of a 10-day meeting of the <ORGANIZATION>Timber
Organization</ORGANIZATION>.
   The organization's members control <PERCENT>95 percent</PERCENT> of the world's
<MONEY>$5.6 billion</MONEY> tropical timber trade.
   As timber trade shifts away from the shrinking forests of <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION>
and southeast <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION>, the mahogany-rich <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> is seen as the next
great source of hardwood.
   But conservationists are worried about the effect on the climate
of uncontrolled logging in the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> basin, a <MONEY>2 million</MONEY>
square-mile region as large as <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> that covers parts of seven
South American countries and contains a third of the world's
rainforest.
   Already the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> forest is disappearing at the rate of some 27
million acres a year, mostly at the hands of small farmers and
ranchers who cut and burn the trees, <PERSON>Markham</PERSON> said.
   ``The rainforest is a gaseous sink for carbon dioxide. The trees
soak it up. If we cut them down, there's no way to get rid of the
gas. And that contributes to the greenhouse effect,'' he said.
   The greenhouse effect is a gradual warming of the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s
surface because of excessive carbon dioxide and pollutants in the
atmosphere that trap the sun's heat, like a greenhouse. It is
thought to be a possible cause of the current drought in the <LOCATION>U.S.
Midwest</LOCATION>.
   The Acre project, which will get about <MONEY>$3 million</MONEY> from the
Brazilan government and the rest from the <ORGANIZATION>Timber Organization</ORGANIZATION>, is
the largest approved since the organization was founded in <DATE>1986</DATE>.
   Smaller conservation programs, similar to the Acre project, were
approved for <LOCATION>Bolivia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Ecuador</LOCATION>.
   Other proposals approved at the Rio meeting were:
   _Development of a ``news market service,'' to help producing
countries market better.
   _Standardization of timber specifications among member
countries, to cut waste caused by conflicting measurements.
   _Improvement of harvesting and processing equipment.
   The next meeting of the organization is scheduled for <DATE>November</DATE>
in <LOCATION>Yokohama</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
