<HEAD>Brazilian Elections Bad News for Ecologists</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEN SILVERSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sweeping victories by
conservatives in last week's congressional and gubernatorial races
will mean bad news for the rain forest and its defenders,
environmentalists say.
   Conservatives won a large majority in last week's voting, and
showed special strength in the nine states of the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> region.
   ``Almost all . . . are totally opposed to ecological concerns
and rational development,'' <PERSON>Fernando Gabeira</PERSON>, a leader of <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s
small <ORGANIZATION>Green Party</ORGANIZATION>, said over the weekend.
   The federal government sets most environmental policy, but
political scientist <PERSON>David Fleischer</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>University of Brasilia</ORGANIZATION>
noted: ``Almost all policy enforcement is carried out by local
authorities. If they show no interest in protecting the
environment, decisions at the federal level lose much of their
impact.''
   Right-wing candidates for governor won outright victories in
three of the nine states and were headed for <DATE>Nov. 25</DATE> runoffs in the
other six.
   Only in two small states, Acre and <LOCATION>Amapa</LOCATION>, did pro-ecology
candidates even get to the runoffs.
   Candidates had to win an absolute majority to take a first-round
victory.
   In congressional races, conservatives won at least 11 of the 13
senate chairs at stake in the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> region and all but a few of
the house seats.
   Rightist populists have long dominated the impoverished region.
Much of their success comes from support by major landowners, who
traditionally control the votes of the rural poor.
   Many voters also view environmentalism as an attempt to block
economic growth and lock the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> into perennial backwardness.
   Slash-and-burn techniques used by ranchers and farmers have
already destroyed about <PERCENT>8 percent</PERCENT> of the 2-million-square-mile
wilderness, according to government figures.
   In Amazonas, the area's largest state, incoming governor
<PERSON>Gilberto Mestrinho</PERSON> favors widescale destruction of the rain forest
to promote large mining and agricultural projects.
   The state's new senator, <PERSON>Amazonino Mendes</PERSON>, proposed handing out
chain saws to settlers to speed the felling of the forest.
   In neighboring <LOCATION>Roraima</LOCATION> state, both gubernatorial finalists
openly opposed federal plans to remove thousands of gold miners
from the territory of the <ORGANIZATION>Yanomami Indians</ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest
remaining primitive tribe.
   The miners illegally search for gold, diamonds and other
minerals on Indian land. Armed clashes and imported diseases killed
about 1,500 of the tribe's remaining 9,000 members in the past
three years.
   The favorite in <LOCATION>Roraima</LOCATION>'s gubernatorial race is <PERSON>Romero Juca</PERSON>, now
on trial for illegally authorizing logging on Indian land when he
was chief of the <ORGANIZATION>National Indian Foundation</ORGANIZATION> in the early <DATE>1980s</DATE>.
   ``The elections in <LOCATION>Roraima</LOCATION> could spell the end for the
<ORGANIZATION>Yanomami</ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON>Fleischer</PERSON> remarked,
   In Para state, the runoff pits anti-ecology candidates <PERSON>Jaber
Barbalho</PERSON> and Sahid Xerfan.
   Para has been the site of repeated clashes between Indians and
miners. Miners have dumped about 600 tons of mercury from gold
prospecting into the <LOCATION>Tapajos River</LOCATION>.
   ``We have no preference in <LOCATION>Para</LOCATION>,'' <PERSON>Gabeira</PERSON> said. ``Neither
possible winner will defend the Indians or the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION>.''
   Big farmers are blamed for most of the violence plaguing the
region. More than 1,000 peasant activists were killed in land
conflicts in the past decade.
   The Rev. <PERSON>Ricardo Resende</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Pastoral Land Commission</ORGANIZATION> said in
a phone interview from Para state, ``The new governors are well
known and most have never demonstrated any interest in protecting
the region's poor. Small farmers will continue to be expelled from
their land.''
   His commission is linked with the <ORGANIZATION>Roman Catholic Church</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Gabeira</PERSON> said the only bright spot was in Acre, home to thousands
of rubber tappers, where <PERSON>Jorge Viana</PERSON> of the pro-environmentalist
<ORGANIZATION>Workers Party</ORGANIZATION> won a spot in the second round.
   His strength is largely attributed to the legacy of
world-renowned unionist and ecologist <PERSON>Chico Mendes</PERSON>, a Workers Party
activist murdered in <DATE>1988</DATE>. Mendes' alleged killers are going on
trial <DATE>Oct. 25</DATE>, and the publicity could boost <ORGANIZATION>Viana</ORGANIZATION>'s campaign.
   There was another note of encouragement to the rain forest's
advocates <DATE>Sunday</DATE> contained in an article in the newspaper Jornal do
Brasil.
   It reported that the area of the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> rain forest destroyed by
fires in <DATE>1990</DATE> was down considerably from last year. Data compiled
by <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>National Institute of Space Research</ORGANIZATION> showed overall
destruction may be down by as much as <PERCENT>50 percent</PERCENT>, the newspaper
said.
   Institute President <PERSON>Marcio Barbosa</PERSON> was quoted as saying that the
space satellite that monitors the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> has been crucial to
efforts to prevent further damage.
</TEXT>
