<HEAD>Brazil Says It Needs $2.2 Billion a Year to Save the Amazon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> it needs
<MONEY>$2.2 billion</MONEY> a year in aid from industrialized countries to stop
the destruction of the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION>, the world's largest wilderness.
   Science and Technology Secretary <PERSON>Jose Goldemberg</PERSON> said the money
would be used to replant deforested areas, relocate settlers and
patrol the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> to stop slash-and-burn devastation of the vast
jungle.
   Scientists say slash-and-burn destruction of <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> rain forest
by ranchers and farmers releases carbon dioxide in the atmosphere
and adds to the greenhouse effect, which increases the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s
temperature.
   ``This wouldn't be charity,'' <PERSON>Goldemberg</PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION>The Associated
Press</ORGANIZATION>. ``The developed countries would be defending their own
interests by stopping the global warming.''
   An average of 8,700 square miles of rain forest has been cut and
burned each year since <DATE>1978</DATE>, or about <PERCENT>8 percent</PERCENT> of the
2-million-square-mile wilderness, <PERSON>Goldemberg</PERSON> said.
   He said the data was obtained from <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Space Research
Institute</ORGANIZATION>, based on 222 Landsat satellite photos of the rain forest.
   Earlier estimates of <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> destruction had ranged from 5 to <PERCENT>20
percent</PERCENT>.
</TEXT>
