<HEAD>Rubber Tapper Says Plotters of Chico Mendes Killing Still at Large
^By PETER MUELLO
^Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A successor to slain <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION>
environmentalist <PERSON>Chico Mendes</PERSON> says the men who planned that killing
continue to threaten witnesses and rubber tappers.
   Osmarino <PERSON>Amancio Rodrigues</PERSON>, 33, said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> that rubber tappers
believe a group of businessmen and ranchers masterminded the <PERSON>Mendes</PERSON>
shooting but were never called to testify in the case.
   ``The head of the snake was not hit,'' <PERSON>Rodrigues</PERSON> told a group of
foreign journalists. ``Those who planned it are still at large.''
   Mendes, a rubber tapper who led a movement to stop destruction
of the rain forest, was shot to death on <DATE>Dec. 22, 1988</DATE>, at his home
in the western <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> town of <LOCATION>Xapuri</LOCATION>.
   A cattle rancher and his sons were arrested for the shooting.
They have not yet been brought to trial.
   <PERSON>Rodrigues</PERSON> said four rubber tappers have been shot to death in
the region since <PERSON>Mendes</PERSON> was slain. One victim, <PERSON>Jose Brito</PERSON>, had been
slated to testify in the trial.
   ``He was going to testify how <PERSON>Chico Mendes</PERSON>' death was planned,''
<PERSON>Rodrigues</PERSON> said. ``But two guys on a motorcycle shot him down right
on the street.''
   Those who oppose the ranchers get frequent anonymous death
threats, he said: ``They call up and say, `Is <PERSON>Chico Mendes</PERSON> OK?
How'd you like to be ``OK'' like Chico?'''
   A prime target is Rodrigues himself, he said. As president of
the rubber tappers union in <LOCATION>Brasileia</LOCATION>, near <LOCATION>Xapuri</LOCATION>, he has emerged
as a leader of conservationist movement, carrying on <PERSON>Mendes</PERSON>'
struggle to save the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> jungle from destruction.
   Rodrigues is constantly accompanied by four union bodyguards
plus a police escort but said he still doesn't feel safe.
   He sharply criticized the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> policy of President <PERSON>Fernando
Collor de Mello</PERSON>, who took office in <DATE>March</DATE>.
   Collor got high marks from conservationists for nominating
renowned ecologist <PERSON>Jose Lutzenberger</PERSON> as Environment Secretary and
ordering the expulsion of gold miners from Indian reservations.
   But <PERSON>Rodrigues</PERSON> said there have been few practical results.
   <PERSON>Rodrigues</PERSON> said the government must learn that the rain forest
can be profitably developed without destroying it. Slash-and-burn
clearing by ranchers and farmers has destroyed an estimated <PERCENT>8
percent</PERCENT> of the 2 million-square-mile <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> wilderness.
   Rubber, <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> nuts, cocoa and tropical fruits are abundant in
the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> but often rot for lack of processing or transportation,
he said.
   Rodrigues has toured <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> to raise money
for the conservation movement. Despite many pledges of funds, not a
cent has reached <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> yet, he said.
   Foreign aid will help environmentalists stand up to ranchers,
mining interests and loggers who buy the votes of the poor and
control local politics, <PERSON>Rodrigues</PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
