<HEAD>Fewer Fires in Amazon This Year But Damage Still Extensive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of fires set in the
<LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> rain forest has dropped from last year but the region is
still suffering extensive damage, government scientists said
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   They say the burning increases the amount of carbon dioxide in
the atmosphere and adds to the greenhouse effect, which causes a
global warming.
   <PERSON>Marcos Pereira</PERSON>, a researcher at the <ORGANIZATION>Space Studies Institute</ORGANIZATION>, said
experts in the past two months detected 59,000 fires that devastated
12,700 square miles of forest _ an area larger than <LOCATION>Maryland</LOCATION>.
   That represents roughly <PERCENT>1.5 percent</PERCENT> of the so-called legal
<LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION>, a 2 million-square-mile region.
   ``We're certainly going to have fewer fires and less destruction
in <DATE>1989</DATE> than in <DATE>1988</DATE>, primarily because we've had unusually heavy
rains this year,'' <PERSON>Pereira</PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION>The Associated Press</ORGANIZATION> by telephone
from <PERSON>Sao Jose dos Campos</PERSON>, 210 miles southwest of Rio.
   In <DATE>1988</DATE>, about 45,600 square miles were destroyed by 205,000
fires, <PERSON>Pereira</PERSON> said.
   The institute monitors fires in the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION> by using satellites
that detect smoke and heat.
   <PERSON>Pereira</PERSON> said the government helped reduce the number of fires,
mainly by suspending incentives for large-scale agricultural and
ranching projects.
   It also began a plan this month to monitor part of the region by
helicopter and fine those found guilty of clearing the forest
illegally.
   Officials handed out <MONEY>$9 million</MONEY> in fines in the first 15 days.
   ``There's a greater awareness of the problem, on the part of the
government and individuals, and that will make it easier to protect
the <LOCATION>Amazon</LOCATION>,'' <PERSON>Pereira</PERSON> said.
   Ranchers and farmers burn off large tracts of the rain forest to
clear land for planting and grazing.
</TEXT>
