<HEAD>Lack Of Resources Hampers Drug War In Bolivia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHIMORE, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trucks and jeeps stand idle for lack of
fuel. Specially trained Bolivian police complain of too little food.
   It hasn't been a good week at this key base of operations for the
national war on drug trafficking.
   Indeed, <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and Bolivian officials say that despite improved
cooperation between their countries, the battle is being lost
because troops don't get enough logistic and economic support.
   ``Our biggest problem is the lack of resources,'' said <PERSON>Travis
Kuykendall</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration</ORGANIZATION>'s attache in
<LOCATION>Bolivia</LOCATION>.
   ``If <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> does not send checks to back us, they should send
us home,'' he said in an interview.
   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> aid for drug interdiction in <LOCATION>Bolivia</LOCATION> was cut from <MONEY>$15
million</MONEY> in <DATE>1988</DATE> to <MONEY>$10 million</MONEY>.
   ``We are doing everything we can to fight the cocaine trade, but
we are fighting a losing war if consumer nations do not increase
their support,'' Information Minister <PERSON>Herman Antelo</PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION>The
Associated Press</ORGANIZATION>.
   An elite U.S.-trained anti-drug police squad of 200 men, known as
the Leopards, and about 30 <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Drug Enforcement and Border Patrol</ORGANIZATION>
agents are based in <LOCATION>Chimore</LOCATION>, a tropical town in the heart of the
<LOCATION>Chapare</LOCATION>. It's a region east of <LOCATION>Cochabamba</LOCATION> city known for its
cultivation of coca, the plant whose dried leaves are the source of
cocaine.
   From Chimore, the men stage raids on cocaine paste processing
pits that lie hidden under the jungle canopy.
   During a weekend visit, however, police said they halted
operations because they did not have fuel for the vehicles or enough
food for the Bolivian forces.
   The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> has donated eight rebuilt Huey helicopters to
cover an area the size of <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>. Five were operational during the
<DATE>weekend</DATE>, but were being deployed in another region of the country,
the Beni plains.
   So coca leaf buying and selling was brisk along the main <LOCATION>Chapare</LOCATION>
highway.
   On better weeks, Bolivian police helped by the American agents
raid hundreds of crude cocaine processing pits.
   But the increased police presence has led many processors to set
up camp outside range of the base's ground vehicles and even
choppers, according to Drug Enforcement agents who asked not to be
identified.
   Gov. <PERSON>Bob Martinez</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Flordia</LOCATION> visited the <LOCATION>Chapare</LOCATION> region <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>
under tight security because of reports an assassination squad of
Colombian drug dealers was in the area.
   ``We had some information that was not confirmed that there was a
Colombian hit team in the area,'' said <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Drug Enforcement agent
<PERSON>Gene Castillo</PERSON>. He accompanied <PERSON>Martinez</PERSON>, who arrived in <LOCATION>Bolivia</LOCATION>
<DATE>Monday</DATE>, and <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Ambassador <PERSON>Robert Gelbard</PERSON> on their tour of the
district. A dozen <ORGANIZATION>DEA</ORGANIZATION> agents and Bolivian police provided security
for the group.
   Martinez, commenting on the importance of the coca plant to the
area farmers, said, ``We can't win the war here, we are going to
have to win it in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>''
   Authorities of both countries say cooperation has increased, and
they are confiscating more chemicals used to process cocaine.
According to the <ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION>, last year they seized 5,549
gallons of ether, 11,158 gallons of sulfuric acid, 927 tons of lime,
10,304 gallons of acetone and 1.5 million gallons of gasoline and
diesel fuel.
   ``Our main purpose in the <LOCATION>Chapare</LOCATION> is to stop the ability to get
precursor chemicals in and cocaine paste out,'' <PERSON>Kuykendall</PERSON> said.
``Then they can't sell paste and farmers will not have a market for
their leaves.''
   Raids on pits where the leaf is mashed and mixed with chemicals
are on the rise. Last year 3,542 pits were raided, compared with
1,112 in <DATE>1987</DATE>, according to the <ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION>. Also last year,
authorities raided 24 laboratories where the paste is converted into
hydrochloric cocaine, the refined powder sniffed by drug users. In
<DATE>1987</DATE>, just eight were raided, the records show.
   But, in almost all cases, the processors manage to flee before
the raids. And the number of pits raided is believed to represent
only a small portion of <LOCATION>Bolivia</LOCATION>'s cocaine industry, whose annual
profits are estimated at <MONEY>$300 million</MONEY>. Little if any real decline in
trafficking has been noted.
   According to <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials, neither <LOCATION>Bolivia</LOCATION> nor the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
government has a single plane capable of intercepting drug flights
out of the country. Large areas bordering <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Peru</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>
have no police presence and drugs also move freely on the rivers.
   The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> bought eight powerful motorboats, and a crew
last week confiscated 950 pounds of cocaine paste on one river. But
they had to stop because they, too, ran out of fuel.
</TEXT>
